Do Not Track:
We and our third-party partners, including Facebook, may employ cookies, pixels, or other tracking technologies to aggregate information regarding your browsing activity over time and across various websites after you have used the site, and to use this information to send targeted ads. We do not respond to "do not track" or other such mechanisms of web browsers currently. If we respond to "do not track" signals in the future, we will then update this Privacy Policy to outline how we do so.
All of these purposes also represent our legitimate interests, which we pursue with the processing of personal data associated with each of them. The legal basis is accordingly Art. 6 para. 1 p. 1 lit. f) DSGVO).
Service Providers:
We employ certain trusted third parties to conduct features and deliver services on our behalf, including, but not limited to, web hosting and maintenance. We will disclose your personal information to those third parties but limited to the amount required to conduct such functions and deliver such services, and only under binding contractual commitments that commit those third parties to maintaining the privacy and security of your information. In addition, we might use the information provided by you through third-party services to deliver the services, which might include accessing the third-party services you selected so that we can provide you with the information you requested. Regarding mobile applications or mobile versions of our websites, we might gather the unique device identifier that has been assigned to the device by phone manufacturers, network providers, or manufacturers of the operating system (the "Device ID"). Device IDs allow app developers, marketers, and others to clearly identify your device to store application preferences and other information. We make commercially reasonable efforts to ensure that our service providers comply with the security standards we apply to your personal information. We might use your device ID to provide security. For instance, if you have activated a function that limits access to a service from a certain device, our systems will be accessing the device ID from any device you try to use to gain access to the services to verify that the device is the authorized device. We might also use device IDs to track suspicious activities. For example, if we discover that a single account on a website is being visited from multiple devices, as identified by tracking the device IDs that are accessing an account, we might reach out to the user to verify that such access has been approved by the user.
